abstract: Parents who depend on hired caregivers were left especially unsettled after a nanny was accused by police of killing two small children on the Upper West Side.
snippet: Parents who depend on hired caregivers were left especially unsettled after a nanny was accused by police of killing two small children on the Upper West Side.
lead_paragraph: It is often the sweetest time of day for harried parents. That magical moment when children retreat from the unpredictable, aggressive city to wash off the dirt of the day and settle into their soothing evening routine of bath time and bedtime stories.

abstract: The Giants won their sixth elimination game of the postseason, advancing to the World Series and suggesting fate is on their side.
snippet: The Giants won their sixth elimination game of the postseason, advancing to the World Series and suggesting fate is on their side.
lead_paragraph: Sometime in the middle of Game 7 falling far short of its expected Game 7-ness, it became clear that karma had become a Giants fan. Sure, the Giants and the Cardinals had basked in her good graces throughout the playoffs, doing their incredible high-wire acts to get to the finale of the National League Championship Series, but the Cardinals did not so much fall off the wire as had it pulled out from under them before they could take a step. Karma could be seen nearby, drumming her fingers against her forearms, trying to look all cute and innocent.

abstract: Tom Wolfe’s novel “Back to Blood” imagines a city where “everybody hates everybody.”
snippet: Tom Wolfe’s novel “Back to Blood” imagines a city where “everybody hates everybody.”
lead_paragraph: In “Back to Blood,” Tom Wolfe tries to do for Miami what he did for New York in “The Bonfire of the Vanities”  and Atlanta in “A Man in Full.”  The result is a soapy, gripping and sometimes glib novel that’s filled with heaps of contrivance and cartoonish antics, but that also stars two characters who attest to Mr. Wolfe’s new and improved ability to conjure fully realized people.
